x4freetext: the 4.5-MV Van de Graaff accelerator
Two 64Zn samples (mass 4.05 +/- 0.05 mg and thickness
266.3 mg/cm2 each) attached back-to-back to the
common cathode were used for simultaneous alpha event
measurements of forward (0 to 90 deg) and backward
(90 to 180 deg) angles.
The isotopic abundance of the 64Zn samples was 99.4%.
Each sample was vacuumevaporated on a tantalum backing
4.8 cm in diameter and 50 mm in thickness.
Twin-gridded ionization chamber.
The shape of the electrodes of the chamber is square,
and the area is 19 x 19 cm2.
The cathode and the anode are aluminum boards coated
with tungsten layer.
The material of the grid wire is tungsten coated with
gold.
The diameter and the spacing of the grid wires are 0.1
and 2.0 mm, respectively.
The working gas of the ionization chamber was Kr +
The pressures of the working gas were 0.90, 1.25, and
1.55 atm for the 2.54, 4.00, and 5.50 MeV
measurements, respectively.
A BF3 long counter as a neutron flux monitor
The  absolute neutron flux was determined by
measuring the fission rate with a  238U foil
(diam.  4.50 cm, mass 7.85 +/- 0.10 mg, and abundance
99.999%) placed  at the third position of the sample
changer.
atom number of the 64Zn sample
atom number of the 238U sample
fission counts (3.0 to 3.4%)
238U fission cross section data
Tables 1-4 of Nucl.Sci.Eng.160(2008)123

x4freetext: tbl.1
A solid Ti-T target and a deuterium gas target
were used asneutron sources. The thickness of the
Ti-T target was 0.80 mg/cm2. Monoenergetic neutrons
were produced through the T(p,n)3He reaction with
the solid target. The energy of the accelerated
protons was 3.35 MeV. The corresponding neutron
energy was 2.54, and the energy spread was 0.03 MeV.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: Uncertainties include those due to:
* the statistics of counts (3.3 to 5%),
* the uncertainty from background
subtraction (4 to 6%),
* the uncertainty of determination of 0 and 90 deg
lines (2 to 5%).

x4freetext: tbl.2
The deuterium gas target was also used to
produce neutrons through the D(d,n)3He reaction. The
length of the gas cell was 2.0 cm, and the deuterium
gas pressure was 2.65 to 2.80 atm. The cell was
separated from the vacuum tube by a 5-mu-m thick
molybdenum film. The energies of the accelerated
deuterons were 1.77 and 2.84 MeV. The corresponding
neutron energies were 4.00 and 5.50 MeV, and the
energy spreads were 0.21 and 0.13 MeV, respectively.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: The errors in include:
* statistical errors (3.3 - 5%),
* background subtraction errors (4 - 6%),
* 90-deg line determination uncertainties (2 - 5%).
